{
  "action_id": "599",
  "action_title": "Can captive breeding have deleterious effects on individual fitness?",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nThree studies of wild populations, wild and captive populations and museum specimens, one replicated, found evidence for\u00a0 potentially deleterious physiological or genetic changes due to captive breeding. These studies did not investigate fitness.\nA study of a wild Mauritius kestrel, Falco punctatus, population derived totally from captive individuals found high inbreeding and a loss of genetic diversity, but this was caused more by the very low population size (four wild birds) than by captivity per se.\nThe museum-based study found reduced relative brain volume in captive wildfowl, compared with wild birds, whilst a comparison of wild and captive populations of white-headed ducks Oxyura leucocephala found lower genetic diversity in captive populations."
}

{
  "action_id": "837",
  "action_title": "Captive breeding Mallorcan midwife toads",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nTwo replicated studies in the UK found that Mallorcan midwife toads produced eggs that were raised to metamorphs or toadlets successfully in captivity. One found that clutches dropped by males were not successfully maintained artificially.\nOne replicated study in the UK found that survival to metamorphosis was 85%. One randomized, replicated, controlled study in the UK found that toads bred in captivity for nine or more generations had slower tadpole development, reduction in one predator defence trait and decreased genetic diversity."
}

{
  "action_id": "836",
  "action_title": "Captive breeding harlequin toads (<i>Atelopus</i> species)",
